INSERT INTO public.learning_articles (slug, title, content, category, content_type, status, excerpt, seo_title, seo_description, reading_time_minutes, difficulty_level, tags, published_at) VALUES

('value-investing', 'Value Investing: Finding Undervalued Opportunities', E'# Value Investing: Finding Undervalued Opportunities\n\nValue investing is the disciplined practice of purchasing securities trading below their intrinsic value—a margin of safety that protects capital while positioning for substantial long-term returns. Pioneered by Benjamin Graham and David Dodd at Columbia Business School in the 1930s and later refined by Warren Buffett, this approach has produced some of the most successful track records in financial history.\n\n## The Philosophy Behind Value Investing\n\nAt its core, value investing rejects the efficient market hypothesis in its strong form. Markets are driven by human participants subject to fear, greed, herd behavior, and cognitive biases. These psychological forces routinely push prices away from fair value, creating opportunities for disciplined investors.\n\nThe central thesis: **price is what you pay, value is what you get.** When a stock trades significantly below its calculated intrinsic value, the gap creates a "margin of safety"—a buffer against analytical errors, unforeseen events, and market downturns.\n\n## How Value Investing Works\n\n### Step 1: Screening for Candidates\n\nValue investors use quantitative filters to narrow the universe:\n\n- **Price-to-Earnings (P/E) Ratio:** Below industry average or below 15x (Graham''s benchmark)\n- **Price-to-Book (P/B) Ratio:** Below 1.5x, ideally below 1.0x\n- **Debt-to-Equity Ratio:** Below 0.5x for conservative screens\n- **Dividend Yield:** Above market average, indicating cash-flow strength\n- **Free Cash Flow Yield:** Above 8%\n- **PEG Ratio:** Below 1.0\n\n### Step 2: Fundamental Analysis\n\n**Financial Statement Analysis:**\n- Revenue trends over 5-10 years\n- Operating margin stability and pricing power\n- Return on Equity (ROE) above 15% sustained over multiple cycles\n- Free cash flow consistency and conversion rate\n- Balance sheet strength: current ratio > 2, interest coverage > 5x\n\n**Competitive Moat Assessment:**\n- Brand strength and customer loyalty\n- Network effects\n- Switching costs\n- Cost advantages and economies of scale\n- Regulatory barriers to entry\n\n**Management Quality:**\n- Capital allocation track record\n- Insider ownership alignment\n- Compensation structure\n- Candor in communications\n\n### Step 3: Intrinsic Value Calculation\n\n**Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) Model:**\n```\nIntrinsic Value = Sum of [FCF_t / (1 + r)^t] + Terminal Value / (1 + r)^n\n\nWhere:\n- FCF_t = Free Cash Flow in year t\n- r = Discount rate (WACC, typically 8-12%)\n- Terminal Value = FCF_n x (1 + g) / (r - g)\n- g = Long-term growth rate (typically 2-3%)\n```\n\n**Earnings Power Value (EPV):**\n```\nEPV = Adjusted Earnings / Cost of Capital\n```\n\n### Step 4: Margin of Safety\n\nGraham recommended purchasing only when the market price is at least **30-50% below intrinsic value.** This accounts for errors in analysis, unexpected deterioration, and broader market declines.\n\n## Entry and Exit Rules\n\n### Entry Criteria\n1. Stock trades at 30%+ discount to conservative intrinsic value\n2. Profitable in at least 7 of last 10 years\n3. Interest coverage > 3x\n4. Clean auditor opinions\n5. Management has significant skin in the game\n\n### Exit Criteria\n1. Price reaches intrinsic value\n2. Fundamentals deteriorate materially\n3. Better opportunity emerges for capital redeployment\n4. Original thesis was wrong\n\n## Risk Management\n\n- Diversify across 15-30 positions\n- Never exceed 10% in a single position at cost\n- No more than 25% in any single sector\n- Rebalance annually\n- Maintain 10-25% cash reserves for market panics\n\n## Value Traps: The Biggest Danger\n\nWarning signs of a value trap:\n- Revenue declining 3+ consecutive years\n- Industry disruption with no adaptation\n- Payout ratio > 100% of free cash flow\n- Serial acquisitions masking organic decline\n- Complex corporate structures\n\n## Famous Value Investors\n\n| Investor | Annualized Return | Period |\n|----------|-------------------|--------|\n| Warren Buffett | ~20% | 1965-2023 |\n| Seth Klarman | ~20% | 1982-2023 |\n| Joel Greenblatt | ~40% | 1985-2006 |\n| Walter Schloss | ~16% | 1956-2002 |\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n1. Value investing is a philosophy requiring deep business understanding\n2. Margin of safety is non-negotiable protection against being wrong\n3. Patience is the value investor''s greatest asset\n4. Avoid value traps by focusing on quality, not just cheapness\n5. The best time to buy is when fear is highest', 'strategies', 'article', 'published', 'Value investing purchases securities below intrinsic value with a margin of safety. Learn screening, valuation, and risk management from Graham and Buffett.', 'Value Investing Strategy: Finding Undervalued Stocks', 'Master value investing with proven techniques. Learn intrinsic value calculation, margin of safety, and how to avoid value traps.', 25, 'intermediate', ARRAY['value-investing','fundamental-analysis','long-term','warren-buffett'], now()),

('growth-investing', 'Growth Investing: Capitalizing on Expanding Companies', E'# Growth Investing: Capitalizing on Expanding Companies\n\nGrowth investing focuses on companies with above-average revenue and earnings growth, often reinvesting profits into expansion rather than paying dividends. This strategy pays a premium today for outsized returns tomorrow.\n\n## The Growth Investing Philosophy\n\nPhilip Fisher pioneered systematic growth investing in "Common Stocks and Uncommon Profits" (1958). His "scuttlebutt method" remains the gold standard for qualitative growth analysis.\n\n## Identifying Growth Stocks\n\n### Quantitative Criteria\n- **Revenue Growth:** 20%+ YoY for 3+ consecutive years\n- **Earnings Growth:** 15%+ annually, accelerating QoQ\n- **Gross Margin:** Above 50% (pricing power)\n- **ROIC:** Above 15%\n- **TAM:** Large and expanding\n- **Net Dollar Retention:** >120% for SaaS\n\n### Qualitative Criteria\n- Market leadership (#1 or #2 position)\n- Strong product-market fit\n- Network effects or platform dynamics\n- Founder-led with long-term vision\n- Multiple expansion vectors\n\n## Growth Investing Frameworks\n\n### The PEG Ratio\n```\nPEG = P/E Ratio / Earnings Growth Rate\nPEG < 1.0 = potentially undervalued growth\nPEG 1.0-2.0 = fairly valued\nPEG > 2.0 = expensive\n```\n\n### Rule of 40 (SaaS)\n```\nScore = Revenue Growth % + Profit Margin %\nScore > 40 = strong\nScore > 60 = exceptional\n```\n\n### The Triple Test\n1. Is the market growing?\n2. Is the company gaining share?\n3. Are margins expanding?\n\nAll three yes = high-conviction growth stock.\n\n## Entry and Exit Rules\n\n### Entry\n1. Revenue growing 20%+ with 3+ year runway\n2. Gross margins stable or expanding\n3. Clear competitive moat\n4. PEG < 2.0\n5. Institutional accumulation\n\n### Exit\n1. Growth decelerates below 15% for 2+ quarters\n2. Margin compression without strategic reason\n3. Competitive disruption capturing share\n4. Key founder/CEO departure\n5. Forward P/E exceeds 100x with decelerating growth\n\n## Risk Management\n\n- Diversify across growth stages\n- Sector balance beyond technology\n- Trailing stops: 20-25% from highs\n- Trim when position exceeds 10% of portfolio\n- Reduce size ahead of binary earnings events\n\n## Common Mistakes\n\n1. Chasing momentum without fundamentals\n2. Ignoring valuation entirely\n3. Holding through fundamental deterioration\n4. Over-concentration in one name\n5. Anchoring to past growth rates\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n1. Growth investing rewards patience in businesses with long runways\n2. Revenue growth, margin expansion, and TAM are the holy trinity\n3. PEG and Rule of 40 provide valuation guardrails\n4. Risk management through diversification and stops is essential\n5. The best growth stocks are bought early and held through volatility', 'strategies', 'article', 'published', 'Growth investing targets companies with above-average earnings expansion. Learn PEG ratio, Rule of 40, and how to identify high-growth stocks.', 'Growth Investing: High-Growth Stock Strategy', 'Learn growth investing frameworks including PEG ratio and Rule of 40. Identify high-growth stocks and manage portfolio risk.', 22, 'intermediate', ARRAY['growth-investing','stock-picking','long-term','earnings-growth'], now()),

('dividend-investing', 'Dividend Investing: Building Passive Income Streams', E'# Dividend Investing: Building Passive Income Streams\n\nDividend investing builds a portfolio of stocks paying regular, growing dividends for reliable passive income and long-term capital appreciation through compounding.\n\n## Why Dividends Matter\n\nSince 1926, dividends contributed approximately **32% of S&P 500 total return** (Hartford Funds). $10,000 invested in 1960 with dividends reinvested grew to ~$5.2M vs ~$627K price-only.\n\n## Key Metrics\n\n### Dividend Yield\n```\nYield = Annual Dividend / Stock Price x 100\n```\n\n### Payout Ratio\n```\nPayout = Dividends / Net Income x 100\nBelow 60%: Healthy\n60-80%: Moderate\nAbove 80%: Risky\nAbove 100%: Unsustainable\n```\n\n### Free Cash Flow Payout\n```\nFCF Payout = Dividends / Free Cash Flow x 100\nBelow 70% is ideal.\n```\n\n## Dividend Aristocrats and Kings\n\n- **Aristocrats:** 25+ consecutive years of increases (J&J, P&G, Coca-Cola)\n- **Kings:** 50+ consecutive years\n- These survived recessions, wars, and pandemics while raising dividends.\n\n## Selection Criteria\n\n1. Yield between 2.5% and 6%\n2. 5+ years consecutive increases\n3. Payout ratio below 65%\n4. Positive FCF in 9 of last 10 years\n5. Debt-to-Equity below 1.0x\n6. Industry leadership with durable moats\n\n## Portfolio Construction\n\n- 15-30 holdings across 8+ sectors\n- Sector targets: Utilities 10-15%, Consumer Staples 15-20%, Healthcare 10-15%, Financials 10-15%, Industrials 10-15%, Tech 10-15%, REITs 5-10%, Energy 5-10%\n\n## The DRIP Strategy\n\nDividend Reinvestment Plans create exponential compounding:\n\n| Year | No DRIP | With DRIP |\n|------|---------|-----------|\n| 10 | $126K | $148K |\n| 20 | $159K | $262K |\n| 30 | $201K | $498K |\n\n*$100K start, 3% yield, 7% dividend growth, 4% price appreciation*\n\n## Risk Management\n\n- Dividend cuts are red flags—sell immediately\n- Investigate high yields (may signal falling price)\n- Interest rate sensitivity in rising-rate environments\n- Avoid over-weighting utilities/REITs\n- Use tax-advantaged accounts\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n1. Dividends provide 30%+ of long-term market returns\n2. Focus on dividend growth rate, not just current yield\n3. Payout ratio and FCF sustainability are critical safety checks\n4. DRIP creates powerful compounding\n5. Diversify across sectors to avoid yield traps', 'strategies', 'article', 'published', 'Dividend investing builds passive income through stocks paying growing dividends. Learn selection criteria, DRIP compounding, and portfolio construction.', 'Dividend Investing: Passive Income Strategy', 'Build passive income with dividend investing. Learn to select dividend aristocrats and compound wealth through reinvestment.', 20, 'beginner', ARRAY['dividend-investing','passive-income','DRIP','income-strategy'], now()),

('index-fund-investing', 'Index Fund Investing: The Passive Wealth Builder', E'# Index Fund Investing: The Passive Wealth Builder\n\nIndex fund investing buys funds tracking a market index rather than picking individual stocks. This passive approach consistently outperforms the majority of actively managed funds.\n\n## The Case for Indexing\n\nJohn Bogle: "Don''t look for the needle in the haystack. Just buy the haystack."\n\n- Over 15 years, **92% of large-cap managers** underperform the S&P 500\n- Average active fund expense: 0.68% vs. 0.03-0.10% for index funds\n\n## How Index Funds Work\n\n- **Market-Cap Weighted:** Larger companies get larger allocations (S&P 500)\n- **Equal Weighted:** Each company same allocation\n- **Factor Weighted:** By value, momentum, quality\n\n### Popular Index Funds\n\n| Index | Example | Expense Ratio |\n|-------|---------|---------------|\n| S&P 500 | VOO, SPY | 0.03% |\n| Total US | VTI | 0.03% |\n| NASDAQ-100 | QQQ | 0.15% |\n| Total World | VT | 0.07% |\n\n## The Three-Fund Portfolio\n\n1. US Total Stock Market (60-70%)\n2. International Stock Market (20-30%)\n3. US Bond Market (0-20%)\n\n### Lifecycle Allocation\n```\nStock % = 110 - Your Age (moderate)\nAge 35 = 75% stocks, 25% bonds\n```\n\n## Dollar-Cost Averaging\n\n- Monthly contributions smooth volatility\n- Automatic investing removes emotion\n- Rebalance annually\n\n## Risk Management\n\n- Time is your primary risk mitigator (20+ years = never negative in S&P 500)\n- Asset allocation controls volatility\n- International diversification reduces single-country risk\n- Rebalancing systematically buys low, sells high\n- Emergency fund first (3-6 months)\n\n## Advantages\n\n- Lowest cost (0.03% expense ratios)\n- Automatic diversification\n- Tax efficient\n- Beats 90%+ of active managers over 15+ years\n- Minimal time required\n\n## Disadvantages\n\n- No outperformance possibility by design\n- Market-cap concentration risk\n- Full drawdown exposure in bear markets\n- Behavioral risk: many panic sell during crashes\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n1. Index investing is the most reliable path to long-term wealth\n2. Low costs compound into massive savings over decades\n3. Three-fund portfolio covers all you need\n4. Dollar-cost averaging removes emotion\n5. The hardest part is doing nothing during crashes', 'strategies', 'article', 'published', 'Index fund investing tracks market indices passively. Learn why it outperforms 90% of active managers and build a three-fund portfolio.', 'Index Fund Investing: Passive Wealth Strategy', 'Master index fund investing. Learn the three-fund portfolio and why passive indexing beats active management.', 18, 'beginner', ARRAY['index-funds','passive-investing','ETF','long-term','bogle'], now()),

('thematic-investing', 'Thematic Investing: Profiting from Megatrends', E'# Thematic Investing: Profiting from Megatrends\n\nThematic investing allocates capital to long-term structural trends—AI, clean energy, demographic shifts—rather than traditional sector classifications.\n\n## Identifying Megatrends\n\n### Technology Themes\n- AI & Machine Learning\n- Cybersecurity\n- Cloud Computing\n- Robotics & Automation\n- Blockchain\n\n### Demographic Themes\n- Aging Population\n- Urbanization\n- Rising Middle Class\n- Remote Work\n\n### Environmental Themes\n- Clean Energy Transition\n- Water Scarcity\n- Circular Economy\n- Electric Vehicles\n\n## Investment Approaches\n\n### Thematic ETFs\n| Theme | ETF | Ticker |\n|-------|-----|--------|\n| AI & Robotics | Global X Robotics | BOTZ |\n| Cybersecurity | First Trust | CIBR |\n| Clean Energy | iShares Global | ICLN |\n\n### Picks and Shovels\nInvest in companies providing essential infrastructure to the theme rather than pure-play end-users.\n\n## Portfolio Construction\n\n### Core-Satellite Model\n- Core (70-80%): Broad market index funds\n- Satellite (20-30%): Thematic positions\n\n### Rules\n- Maximum 5-7 themes\n- 5-10% per theme\n- Stagger entry across time\n- Review quarterly\n\n## Risk Management\n\n- Theme duration risk: some take decades\n- Valuation bubbles in popular themes\n- Concentration in narrow ETFs\n- Regulatory risk\n- Technology prediction difficulty\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n1. Thematic investing captures structural change returns\n2. Use core-satellite approach\n3. Picks and shovels often outperform pure plays\n4. Be disciplined about valuation\n5. Review and reallocate as themes evolve', 'strategies', 'article', 'published', 'Thematic investing targets megatrends like AI, clean energy, and demographic shifts. Learn portfolio construction and risk management.', 'Thematic Investing: Megatrend Strategy', 'Profit from megatrends with thematic investing. Build a core-satellite portfolio targeting AI, clean energy, and more.', 18, 'intermediate', ARRAY['thematic-investing','megatrends','AI','clean-energy'], now()),

('esg-investing', 'ESG Investing: Sustainable and Responsible Returns', E'# ESG Investing: Sustainable and Responsible Returns\n\nESG integrates Environmental, Social, and Governance factors into investment analysis alongside traditional financial metrics—a framework for identifying risks and opportunities that traditional analysis may miss.\n\n## The Three Pillars\n\n### Environmental\n- Carbon emissions and climate risk\n- Resource efficiency\n- Pollution and liabilities\n- Clean technology adoption\n\n### Social\n- Labor practices and fair wages\n- Diversity and inclusion\n- Product safety\n- Data privacy\n- Human rights\n\n### Governance\n- Board independence and diversity\n- Executive compensation alignment\n- Shareholder rights\n- Accounting transparency\n- Anti-corruption policies\n\n## ESG Approaches\n\n### 1. Negative Screening\nExclude tobacco, weapons, fossil fuels, etc.\n\n### 2. Positive Screening (Best-in-Class)\nSelect highest ESG-rated companies per sector.\n\n### 3. ESG Integration\nSystematically incorporate ESG into financial valuation models.\n\n### 4. Impact Investing\nTarget measurable positive outcomes: green bonds, social impact bonds.\n\n### 5. Shareholder Advocacy\nUse ownership rights to influence corporate behavior through proxy voting and engagement.\n\n## ESG Data Sources\n\n- MSCI ESG Ratings (AAA to CCC)\n- Sustainalytics risk scores\n- CDP climate data\n- Bloomberg ESG metrics\n\n## Performance Evidence\n\n- Meta-analysis of 2,200 studies (NYU Stern): ESG integration associated with similar or better performance\n- MSCI World ESG Leaders matched or outperformed over 10+ years\n- During COVID crash (Q1 2020): ESG funds had 20% less drawdown\n\n## Risks and Criticisms\n\n- Greenwashing: overstated ESG credentials\n- Lack of standardization across rating agencies\n- Data gaps in emerging markets\n- Sector bias (tech scores well, energy scores poorly)\n- Political scrutiny in some jurisdictions\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n1. ESG is a risk management framework, not just ethics\n2. Multiple approaches from exclusion to deep integration\n3. Performance data supports ESG as financially sound\n4. Due diligence required to avoid greenwashing\n5. ESG factors are increasingly material to long-term returns', 'strategies', 'article', 'published', 'ESG investing integrates environmental, social, and governance factors. Learn sustainable portfolio approaches without sacrificing returns.', 'ESG Investing: Sustainable Strategy Guide', 'Master ESG investing. Integrate environmental, social, and governance factors for sustainable returns.', 20, 'intermediate', ARRAY['ESG','sustainable-investing','responsible-investing','green-finance'], now());